VERT_EXTENT_FAULT: Faults present, displacement is less than thickness of the seal
REMARKS: Extensive carbonate cementation in Cormorant field; Formation consists of interbedded mudstones and sandstones and is compartmentalised. Therefore pressure capacity estimation method is most appropriate.

CAP_EST_METHOD: Pore vol and storage eff coefficient

REMARKS: Has plenty of oil shows but oil saturation is low, so no hydrocarbon field daughter units. No evidence of compartmentalisation so no aquifer daughter units described. See Gluyas, J & Swarbrick, R. 2004. Petroleum Geoscience, Blackwell, pp. 252-258.

SEAL: Kimmeridge Clay Fm/Cromer Knoll Group mudstones

REMARKS: This covers the main Brae fields, see e.g. Fletcher, K.J. 2001. The Central Brae Field, Blocks 16/07a, 16/07b, UK North Sea. In Gluyas, J.G. & Hichens, H.M. (eds). United Kingdom Oil and Gas Fields, Millenium Commemorative Volume. Geol. Soc. London Mem.
Heavily compartmentalised by faults in some fields (Don). Mid-Brent shale divides Group almost into two.
There is oil in the Brora Coal Fm in the Beatrice field

Fracture permeability is present in the Buchan field. Matrix porosity and permeability is very low. Ref: Edwards, C.W. 1991. The Buchan Field, Blocks 20/5a and 21/1a, North Sea, Geological Society, London, Memoir 14; p. 253-259. Min and max areas v diff.

SEAL: Kimmeridge Clay Fm/Cromer Knoll Gp mudstones

REMARKS: Poorly known. See Leeder, M.R. & Boldy S.R. 1990. The Carboniferous of the Outer Moray Firth Basin, Quadrants 14 and 15, Central North Sea. Marine and Petroleum Geology, 7, 29-37.

SEAL: Poorly sealed by Brora Coal Formation
REMARKS: Probably in hydraulic continuity with overlying Brora Coal Formation

SEAL: Heather/ Kimmeridge Clay/ Cromer Knoll Gp mudstones

REMARKS: Potential interference with hydrocarbon production. Thickness very variable.
